Right Dan and SW,<br><br>
What I find most bothersome is that now, as with Vietnam those in power are making choices based on what is best. But... not what is best for the people of the world, or the US people, but what is best for industry. For the Global economy. The war with Iraq (yes that war is happening now) will go on for a long time after any weapons cease to fire. It is a war to control the resources that are abundant in the middle east. OIL!! We want the oil in the middle east. Good cheap oil, with unrestricted flow. That is why we were upset about Iraq and Kuwait. Our oil was threatened. Why did we go to stop Iraq, when we ignored Eritria? Why do we watch the carnage in Africa with little or no intervention? <br><br>
I for one could live with higher oil prices and peace and justice. I have a hard time living with killing for oil. War to better those who are rich with money and power at the expense of the working men and women who go to fight.<br><br>
If we lived in Iraq, and a foreign power was coming to invade our contry what would we do? From reading this site, I think we would take up arms and fight 'til the death if necessary. That is what the Iraqi people are doing. Sadaam is their problem, like Clinton is ours. If I want him our of office I say it is ours to do. If a foreign power tries to do it then I will be there to fight against their invasion. So how do we counter this? <br><br>
I don't know how we should proceed from the place we are at today, but I do know that there is a problem with the very construct of the situation and I am saddened by it and athe prospect that people will die for another cause that cannot stand the test of time. <br><br>
Tomorrow I am going to see the Vietnam War Memorial. I have never been there. I don't know how I will react or what to expect when I am there, but I know I will be hoping to find some answers and some peace from the torment I feel about being part of a divided America. 
